  "prompt": "Why do many people dislike Chetan Bhagat's novels so much?",
  "response": "There are several reasons why Chetan Bhagat's novels are often criticized:\n\n1. Writing Quality\n- Simple and unrefined language\n- Weak narrative structure\n- Lack of literary depth\n- Repetitive plot lines\n\n2. Stereotypical Characters\n- Poorly developed and one-dimensional characters\n- Often representing stereotypical urban Indian youth\n- Lack of character complexity\n\n3. Commercial Approach\n- Perceived as writing purely for commercial success\n- Focusing more on marketability than literary merit\n- Prioritizing mass appeal over artistic quality\n\n4. Predictable Storylines\n- Formulaic plots\n- Often revolving around love, relationships, and campus life\n- Lacking originality and nuance\n\n5. Cultural Representation\n- Criticized for superficial representation of Indian society\n- Oversimplifying complex social issues\n- Catering to a narrow demographic\n\n6. Academic Background\n- Some literary critics view his work as lacking serious literary value\n- Considered \"pulp fiction\" or \"low-brow literature\"\n\n7. Perceived Commercialization of Literature\n- Seen as contributing to declining literary standards\n- Prioritizing quick reads and mass consumption\n\nDespite criticism, Bhagat remains popular among many young readers for his accessible writing style and relatable narratives.",
